compilation commands:
$ gcc -o mypwd mypwd.c
$ gcc -o myecho myecho.c
$ gcc -o mycp mycp.c
$ gcc -o mymv mymv.c

example of the output:

PWD EXAMPLE:
esmael@esmael-VirtualBox:~/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4$ ./mypwd
/home/esmael/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4


ECHO EXAMPLE:
esmael@esmael-VirtualBox:~/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4$ ./myecho Assignment 4 solution
Assignment 4 solution 


CP EXAMPLE:
esmael@esmael-VirtualBox:~/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4$ ./mycp myecho.c t1.txt
esmael@esmael-VirtualBox:~/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4$ cat t1.txt
#include <stdio.h>

int main (int argc, char * argv[])
{
	for (int i=1; i<argc; i++)
	printf("%s ", argv[i]);
	printf("\n");
}


MV EXAMPLE:
esmael@esmael-VirtualBox:~/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4$ ./mymv t1.txt t2.txt
esmael@esmael-VirtualBox:~/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4$ ls
mycp  mycp.c  myecho  myecho.c  mymv  mymv.c  mypwd  mypwd.c  t2.txt
esmael@esmael-VirtualBox:~/linux-course/Assignments/Assignment4$ cat t2.txt
#include <stdio.h>

int main (int argc, char * argv[])
{
	for (int i=1; i<argc; i++)
	printf("%s ", argv[i]);
	printf("\n");
}
